By the definition of a \textbf{critical number}, we must find the $x$
for which $\displaystyle f'(x) = 0$ or for which $\displaystyle f'(x)$
does not exist:

\begin{align*}
f(x) &= 63 x^{\frac{2}{7}} - 14 x^{\frac{9}{7}}
\\ f'(x) &= \frac{2}{7} \cdot 63 x^{\frac{2}{7} - 1} - \frac{9}{7} \cdot 14 x^{\frac{9}{7} - 1}
\\ &= 18x^{-\frac{5}{7}} - 18x^{\frac{2}{7}}
\\ &= 18x^{-\frac{5}{7}}(1 - x)
\end{align*}

Setting $\displaystyle f'(x) = 0$ and applying the zero product
property:

\begin{align*}
18x^{-\frac{5}{7}}(1 - x) &= 0
\\ 18x^{-\frac{5}{7}} = 0 ,\,\,\,\, 1-x &= 0
\\ {\color{red} \frac{18}{x^{\frac{5}{7}}} = 0,}\,\,\,\, 1-x &= 0
\\ x &= 1
\end{align*}

Note that $18x^{-\frac{5}{7}}$ is never equal to zero on the interval
$(-\infty, \infty)$. However, $18x^{-\frac{5}{7}}$ is undefined at
$x = 0$, so $\displaystyle f'(x)$ does not exist at $x = 0$.

Therefore the critical numbers of $f$ are $x = {\color{blue} 0,1}$.
